    <help><![CDATA[
**Assemblytics** is an application for detecting and analyzing variants from a de novo genome
assembly aligned to a reference genome. It incorporates a unique anchor filtering approach to
increase robustness to repetitive elements, and identifies six classes of variants based on their
distinct alignment signatures. Assemblytics can be applied both to comparing aberrant genomes,
such as human cancers, to a reference, or to identify differences between related species.
Multiple visualizations enable in-depth explorations of the genomic distributions of variants.

To run, first align your assembly to a reference genome using **Nucmer** (part of the MUMmer
package, available in Galaxy). Make sure to select the **delta** output format. You can then
use the resulting delta file as input to Assemblytics.

**Parameters**

- ``Unique sequence length required``: An anchor for determining whether a sequence is unique
  enough to safely call variants from — an alternative to the mapping quality filter used in
  read alignment. The default of 10,000 means a variant must be anchored by at least 10,000 bp
  of unique sequence. This is a stringent filter; reduce it for more fragmented assemblies or
  more repetitive genomes.

- ``Minimum variant size``: Minimum variant size to report. Defaults to 50 bp; variants smaller
  than this will not be reported. Reduce this value if you are interested in smaller variants
  (50 bp is the common threshold for structural variants).

- ``Maximum variant size``: Maximum variant size to report. Defaults to 10,000 bp. Increasing
  this may reveal larger variants, but can also introduce spurious calls caused by alignment
  artifacts, especially with fragmented assemblies or repetitive genomes.

**Output files**

- ``output.Assemblytics_assembly_stats.txt``: Statistics on your input assemblies.

- ``output.Assemblytics_structural_variants.summary``: Text summary of structural variations (also available as a CSV).

- ``output.Assemblytics_structural_variants.bed``: BED file of structural variations.

- ``output.variants_between_alignments.bed``: BED file of variants found between alignments.

- ``output.variants_within_alignments.bed``: BED file of variants found within alignments.

- ``output.Assemblytics.unique_length_filtered.delta.gz``: Delta file of unique alignments after applying the unique-length filter.

- ``output.info.csv``: Summary information on all alignments.

- ``output.coords.csv``: All alignments as a CSV (also available as a tabular file).

- ``output.coords.query.genome``: Length of each query contig with at least one alignment.

- ``output.coords.ref.genome``: Length of each reference contig with at least one alignment.

- ``output.oriented_coords.csv``: All alignments with coordinates oriented to the reference genome.

**Visualizations**

- ``output.Assemblytics.Dotplot_filtered.png``: Dotplot of the filtered alignments used for variant calling.

- ``output.Assemblytics.Nchart.png``: N-chart of the input assemblies (also available as PDF).

- ``output.Assemblytics.size_distributions.all_variants.50-500.png``: Size distribution of variants between 50 and 500 bp (also available as PDF).

- ``output.Assemblytics.size_distributions.all_variants.500-10000.png``: Size distribution of variants between 500 and 10,000 bp (also available as PDF).

- ``output.Assemblytics.size_distributions.all_variants.log_all_sizes.png``: Size distribution of all variants on a log scale (also available as PDF).

    ]]></help>

